Yes, you are right. Both 

    pending$ = this.store.pipe(select(fromAuth.selectLoginPagePending));
    error$ = this.store.pipe(select(fromAuth.selectLoginPageError));


and 

    pending$ = this.store.select(fromAuth.selectLoginPagePending);
    error$ = this.store.select(fromAuth.selectLoginPageError);


carry out the same function, which is to obtain a slice of the store state , as described on the NgRX documentation on [selectors][1].

However, the `pipe()` utility allows you to chain the selector with [RxJS pipeable operators][2], such as `scan()`, and `filter()`, allowing you to carry out other operations such as state transitions.


